  "text": "## Health Check Endpoint Implementations Across Go Projects\n\n### Kubernetes (kubernetes/kubernetes)\n\nKubernetes implements a sophisticated health check system with three separate endpoints:\n\n**Endpoints:**\n- `/healthz` - General health check (deprecated, will be removed)\n- `/livez` - Liveness probe\n- `/readyz` - Readiness probe\n\n**Key Files:**\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/healthz/healthz.go` (lines 38-180): Defines the `HealthChecker` interface and handler registration functions. `InstallHandler()` registers handlers for `/healthz`, `InstallReadyzHandler()` registers `/readyz`, and `InstallLivezHandler()` registers `/livez`.\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/genericapiserver.go` (lines 205-207): The `GenericAPIServer` struct contains three health check registries: `healthzRegistry`, `readyzRegistry`, and `livezRegistry`.\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/options/etcd.go` (lines 360-410): Adds etcd-specific health checks. Creates `etcd-readiness` grouped checks that verify etcd connectivity by executing readiness verification functions via `CreateReadyCheck()`. Also adds etcd-override checks for multi-server configurations.\n- `cmd/kube-scheduler/app/server.go` (lines 373-376): Example of how health checks are installed - calls `InstallHandler()`, `InstallLivezHandler()`, and `InstallReadyzHandler()` with respective check lists.\n\n**Built-in Health Checks:**\n- `PingHealthz` (line 52): Simple check that always returns true\n- `LogHealthz` (line 67): Checks that logging isn't blocked by monitoring klog flush timing\n- `NewInformerSyncHealthz()` (line 105): Waits for cache sync on informers\n- `NewShutdownHealthz()` (line 121): Fails when shutdown signal is received\n- `etcd-readiness`: Custom checks for etcd connectivity\n\n**Architecture:** Uses a registry pattern where checks are added via `AddHealthChecks()` or `AddReadyzChecks()` methods. Each check can be excluded via query parameters (e.g., `?exclude=check-name`). Supports grouped checks for organizing related health checks.\n\n---\n\n### Grafana (grafana/grafana)\n\nGrafana implements both a simple `/healthz` endpoint and a comprehensive `/api/health` endpoint with database checks:\n\n**Endpoints:**\n- `/healthz` - Always returns 200 OK if server is running (pkg/api/http_server.go, line 756)\n- `/api/health` - Returns health status with database connectivity check (pkg/api/http_server.go, line 785)\n- `/livez`, `/readyz` - Proxied to API server (pkg/services/apiserver/service.go, lines 212-214)\n\n**Key Files:**\n- `pkg/api/http_server.go` (lines 755-766): `healthzHandler()` is a simple handler that returns 200 OK with \"Ok\" response. Only responds to GET/HEAD requests to `/healthz`.\n- `pkg/api/http_server.go` (lines 785-820): `apiHealthHandler()` checks database connectivity and returns HTTP 200 if healthy or 503 if the database is failing. Returns JSON response with database status and version information (if not anonymized).\n- `pkg/api/health.go` (lines 10-25): `databaseHealthy()` performs actual health check by executing `SELECT 1` query against the database. Caches result for 5 seconds to avoid excessive database queries.\n- `pkg/services/apiserver/service.go` (lines 212-215): Registers routes for `/livez`, `/readyz`, `/healthz`, and `/openapi` as proxy groups.\n\n**Database Check:** The main health check verifies database connectivity by executing a simple SELECT 1 query with 5-second caching to balance responsiveness and database load.\n\n---\n\n### Prometheus (prometheus/prometheus)\n\nPrometheus uses the `/-/` prefix convention with two health status endpoints:\n\n**Endpoints:**\n- `/-/healthy` - Returns 200 OK if Prometheus is healthy (web/web.go, lines 591-597)\n- `/-/ready` - Returns 200 OK only if ready to serve traffic, 503 if stopping (web/web.go, lines 598-604)\n\n**Key Files:**\n- `web/web.go` (lines 109-115): Defines `ReadyStatus` enum with three states: `NotReady`, `Ready`, and `Stopping`.\n- `web/web.go` (lines 591-604): Endpoint handlers registered with routes. `/-/healthy` always succeeds, while `/-/ready` wraps the handler with `readyf()` (the `testReady` function) to conditionally return success (200) or failure (503).\n- `web/web.go` (lines 642-651): `SetReady()` method updates the ready status and corresponding prometheus metric `prometheus_ready` gauge. Sets to 1 when Ready, 0 otherwise.\n- `web/web.go` (lines 658-677): `testReady()` function checks the current ready status. Returns 200 if Ready, 503 if NotReady (with `X-Prometheus-Stopping: false` header) or Stopping (with `X-Prometheus-Stopping: true` header). This allows graceful removal from load balancers during shutdown.\n- `web/web.go` (lines 467): Uses `readyf := h.testReady` to wrap critical endpoints like `/federate` (line 487) and `/consoles` (line 491).\n\n**Ready Status Management:** The ready status is managed externally by the main server initialization code (`cmd/prometheus/main.go`), which sets the Handler's ready status during startup once TSDB and other components are initialized. The `X-Prometheus-Stopping` header indicates whether the server is shutting down, allowing orchestration systems to distinguish between \"not ready yet\" (false) and \"shutting down\" (true) states for proper load balancer behavior.\n"
